According to the specialists, this animal has a chestnut plumage in the upper area and a pale or carotenoid tonality in the lower part.
The finding also allows us to better understand the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the plumage of dinosaurs does not have a well-developed axis, called rachis, but does have other features of the feathers (birds and barbles), the researchers concluded that it is likely that the rachis is the result of a subsequent evolutionary development of these other characteristics.
The structure of the plumage suggests that its function was not related to flight, but that it was used to regulate the temperature or as an indicator of the same. The researchers argue that although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, analyzed sample has characteristics of an adult plumage and not of a chick.
