Technological determinism is a concept that comprises, pragmatically, a wide range of ideas, from the momentum or technological imperative to a strict sense that there is an underlying logic that drives the fate of humanity and that relates to the laws of science and how they are reflected in technology.
Almost all the interpretations of technological determinism have two general have two general ideas: that technological development itself is deployed on an independent path independent of any cultural or political influence and that, at the same time, the technology has “effects” in societies that are inherent and not socially conditioned.
To give an example, one could argue that the existence of cars necessarily derives from road development.
However, a national road network is not economically viable for a reduced volume of cars volume, which is why new manufacturing techniques are being designed to reduce the costs of owning a vehicle.
The massive use of cars also leads to increased incidence in traffic accidents, leading to the development of new techniques in the field of health to repair damaged bodies.
